Demonstratives (Determinatives, eta). — (1) Significa- tion: Hic, ‘ this (here) ' (including for hic, as well as the other de- monstratives, their adverbial forms), contrasted with ille, ‘ yonder,' is used of what is locally close or temporally near by, ille being used of the remote3 contrasted with iste, hic relates to the first person, while iste is employed of the second. In this usage, as the speaker changes, hic becomes iste, or vice versa, e.g. hosce (822) becomes istis (823), and hasce becomes istas (988) ; cf. 918-919, where isti is echoed by huic, and in 964-965, istic by hic. But iste may be used to make an abusive or deprecatory reference to a third person or class of persons (274, 480, 655, 668, 798 [3], 843, 854, 918), even persons in the audi- ence (356). Further, the distinction between these pronouns seems now and then to break down, e.g. huc (835) is echoed by illic (836). See also notes 011 913, 919, and 921. If iste is contemptuous, ille is sometimes honorific (398), and sometimes connotes -‘ the proverbial‚’ ‘ the typical ’ (see note on 362).
